<collectingCountry id="F33A1B96F779B138B250FAA031B0463B" box="[789,905,1375,1401]" name="Botswana" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Botswana</collectingCountry>
are very difficult to identify. His travels and camp sites were summarised by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F779B138B364FA7C312C46DF" author="Gyldenstolpe, N." box="[545,789,1411,1437]" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" pagination="264 - 292" refId="ref28785" refString="Gyldenstolpe, N. (1934) The travels and collections of Johan August Wahlberg, 1810 - 1856: a pioneer naturalist in South Africa. Ibis, 76, 264 - 292. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1474 - 919 X. 1934. tb 01567. x" type="journal article" year="1934">Gyldenstolpe (1934)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F779B138B211FA7C31C646DF" author="Brinck, P." box="[852,1023,1410,1437]" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" refId="ref28132" refString="Brinck, P. (1955) Swedish exploration of South African animal life during 200 years. In: Hanstrom, B., Brinck, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (Eds.), South African Animal Life. Vol. 1. Almquist &amp; Wiksell, Stockholm, pp. 11 - 61." type="book" year="1955">Brinck (1955)</bibRefCitation>
, but many of the sites lack names or any reference to named places. From 
<date id="FF937DC6F779B138B33DFA58314C4683" box="[632,885,1446,1473]" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" value="1855-07" valueMax="1855-10-31" valueMin="1855-07-00">July to October 1855</date>
, Wahlberg and his companions travelled north along the Thaoge River, and then the 
<collectingRegion id="49E995E4F779B138B31CFA3430EB46A7" box="[601,722,1483,1509]" country="Namibia" name="Kavango West" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Okavango</collectingRegion>
River after passing the confluence between the Thaoge and Jao rivers. On 25 July the group passed Mapororo Lagoon and camped at or near the confluence of the Thaoge and the Jao (Ng-Gokha) Rivers, at a place called “Embana” (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F779B138B21AF9EC3692456C" author="Craig, A. &amp; Hummel, C." box="[863,1195,1555,1582]" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" refId="ref28290" refString="Craig, A. &amp; Hummel, C. (1994) Johan August Wahlberg. Travel Journals (and Some Letters) South Africa and Namibia / Botswana, 1838 - 1856. Translated from Swedish by Michael Roberts. Series 2. No. 23. Van Riebeeck Society, Cape Town, 249 pp." type="book" year="1994">Craig &amp; Hummel 1994: 169</bibRefCitation>
) (Embana River is a local name for the Thaoge near the 
<collectingRegion id="49E995E4F779B138B37EF9C8308A4513" box="[571,691,1591,1617]" country="Namibia" name="Kavango West" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Okavango</collectingRegion>
/Jao junction; Wendy Borello, pers. comm.). The Thaoge River becomes the 
<collectingRegion id="49E995E4F779B138B075F9A433904537" box="[304,425,1627,1653]" country="Namibia" name="Kavango West" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Okavango</collectingRegion>
River at this point. The group continued north along the 
<collectingRegion id="49E995E4F779B138B503F9A436864537" box="[1094,1215,1627,1653]" country="Namibia" name="Kavango West" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Okavango</collectingRegion>
River, collecting a female 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D2085F779B138B1B5F98033A645DA" authorityName="Wahlberg" authorityYear="1856" box="[240,415,1663,1688]" class="Aves" family="Prionopidae" genus="Prionops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="retzii">
<emphasis id="B9598714F779B138B1B5F98033A645DA" box="[240,415,1663,1688]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Prionops retzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 23 July, an African Palm-Swift 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D2085F779B138B200F980362C45DA" baseAuthorityName="Lichtenstein" baseAuthorityYear="1823" box="[837,1045,1663,1689]" class="Aves" family="Apodidae" genus="Cypsiurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parvus">
<emphasis id="B9598714F779B138B200F980362C45DA" box="[837,1045,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Cypsiurus parvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 31 July [erroneously labelled with the locality Molopo River (= Mapororo River)], and two more specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D2085F779B138B517F95C373945FE" authorityName="Wahlberg" authorityYear="1856" box="[1106,1280,1699,1724]" class="Aves" family="Prionopidae" genus="Prionops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="retzii">
<emphasis id="B9598714F779B138B517F95C373945FE" box="[1106,1280,1699,1724]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Prionops retzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(one of them the 
<typeStatus id="5496E5A4F779B138B187F938330945A0" box="[194,304,1735,1762]" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">lectotype</typeStatus>
) on 3 August along the way. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F779B138B25BF93831FF45A3" author="Brinck, P." box="[798,966,1734,1761]" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" refId="ref28132" refString="Brinck, P. (1955) Swedish exploration of South African animal life during 200 years. In: Hanstrom, B., Brinck, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (Eds.), South African Animal Life. Vol. 1. Almquist &amp; Wiksell, Stockholm, pp. 11 - 61." type="book" year="1955">Brinck (1955)</bibRefCitation>
, the group eventually reached Libebe (= Andara, 
<collectingCountry id="F33A1B96F779B138B1B9F914335D4447" box="[252,356,1771,1797]" name="Namibia" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Namibia</collectingCountry>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE193DC1F779B138B02AF91433E54447" box="[367,476,1771,1797]" degrees="18" direction="south" minutes="40" orientation="latitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" precision="925" value="-18.666666">18° 40’ S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE193DC1F779B138B0ADF914306F4447" box="[488,598,1771,1797]" degrees="21" direction="east" minutes="27" orientation="longitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" precision="925" value="21.45">21° 27’ E</geoCoordinate>
) on 14 August. The type locality for 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D2085F779B138B546F91436884446" authorityName="Wahlberg" authorityYear="1856" box="[1027,1201,1771,1796]" class="Aves" family="Prionopidae" genus="Prionops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="retzii">
<emphasis id="B9598714F779B138B546F91436884446" box="[1027,1201,1771,1796]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="533">Prionops retzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is vague, but nevertheless the type locality suggested by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F779B138B308F8F03153446B" author="Gyldenstolpe, N." box="[589,874,1807,1833]" pageId="12" pageNumber="533" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref28755" refString="Gyldenstolpe, N. (1926) Types of birds in the Royal Natural History Museum in Stockholm. Arkiv f or Zoologi, 19, 1 - 116." type="journal article" year="1926">Gyldenstolpe (1926: 40)</bibRefCitation>
is reasonable and should stand. The species was named after Professor Anders Adolf Retzius (1796–1860), who was married to Emilia Sofia Wahlberg, sister of J.A. Wahlberg and Peter F. Wahlberg, and one of the sponsors of Wahlberg’s expedition.
</paragraph>
